#: ../../../configuration.rst:-1
msgid ""
"Learn how to configure Spack using its flexible YAML-based system. This "
"guide covers the different configuration scopes and provides links to "
"detailed documentation for each configuration file, helping you customize "
"Spack to your specific needs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:13
msgid "Configuration Files"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:15
msgid ""
"Spack has many configuration files. Here is a quick list of them, in case "
"you want to skip directly to specific docs:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:18
msgid ":ref:`concretizer.yaml <concretizer-options>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:19
msgid ":ref:`config.yaml <config-yaml>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:20
msgid ":ref:`include.yaml <include-yaml>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:21
msgid ":ref:`mirrors.yaml <mirrors>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:22
msgid ":ref:`modules.yaml <modules>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:23
msgid ""
":ref:`packages.yaml <packages-config>` (including :ref:`compiler "
"configuration <compiler-config>`)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:24
msgid ":ref:`repos.yaml <repositories>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:25
msgid ":ref:`toolchains.yaml <toolchains>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:27
msgid ""
"You can also add any of these as inline configuration in the YAML manifest "
"file (``spack.yaml``) describing an :ref:`environment <environment-"
"configuration>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:30
msgid "YAML Format"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:32
msgid ""
"Spack configuration files are written in YAML. We chose YAML because it's "
"human-readable but also versatile in that it supports dictionaries, lists, "
"and nested sections. For more details on the format, see `yaml.org <https://"
"yaml.org>`_. Here is an example ``config.yaml`` file:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:37 ../../../configuration.rst:307
msgid ""
"config:\n"
"  install_tree:\n"
"    root: $spack/opt/spack\n"
"  build_stage:\n"
"  - $tempdir/$user/spack-stage\n"
"  - ~/.spack/stage"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:46
msgid ""
"Each Spack configuration file is nested under a top-level section "
"corresponding to its name. So, ``config.yaml`` starts with ``config:``, "
"``mirrors.yaml`` starts with ``mirrors:``, etc."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:51
msgid ""
"Validation and autocompletion of Spack config files can be enabled in your "
"editor using `JSON Schema Store <https://www.schemastore.org/>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:56
msgid "Configuration Scopes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:58
msgid ""
"Spack pulls configuration data from files in several directories. There are "
"multiple configuration scopes. From lowest to highest precedence:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:62
msgid ""
"**defaults**: Stored in ``$(prefix)/etc/spack/defaults/``. These are the "
"\"factory\" settings. Users should generally not modify the settings here, "
"but should override them in other configuration scopes. The defaults here "
"will change from version to version of Spack."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:67
msgid ""
"**system**: Stored in ``/etc/spack/``. These are settings for this machine "
"or for all machines on which this file system is mounted. The systm scope "
"overrides the defaults scope. It can be used for settings idiosyncratic to a "
"particular machine, such as the locations of compilers or external packages. "
"Be careful when modifying this scope, as changes here affect all Spack users "
"on a machine. Before putting configuration here, instead consider using the "
"``site`` scope, which only affects the spack instance it's part of."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:74
msgid ""
"**site**: Stored in ``$(prefix)/etc/spack/site/``. Settings here affect only "
"*this instance* of Spack, and they override the defaults and system scopes. "
"The site scope is intended for site-wide settings on multi-user machines (e."
"g., for a common Spack instance)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:78
msgid ""
"**plugin**: Read from a Python package's entry points. Settings here affect "
"all instances of Spack running with the same Python installation. This scope "
"takes higher precedence than site, system, and default scopes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:82
msgid ""
"**user**: Stored in the home directory: ``~/.spack/``. These settings affect "
"all instances of Spack and take higher precedence than site, system, plugin, "
"or defaults scopes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:85
msgid ""
"**spack**: Stored in ``$(prefix)/etc/spack/``. Settings here affect only "
"*this instance* of Spack, and they override ``user`` and lower configuration "
"scopes. This is intended for project-specific or single-user spack "
"installations. This is the the topmost built-in spack scope, and modifying "
"it gives you full control over configuration scopes. For example, it defines "
"the ``user``, ``site``, and ``system`` scopes, so you can use it to remove "
"them completely if you want."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:91
msgid ""
"**environment**: When using Spack :ref:`environments`, Spack reads "
"additional configuration from the environment file. See :ref:`environment-"
"configuration` for further details on these scopes. Environment scopes can "
"be referenced from the command line as ``env:name`` (e.g., to reference "
"environment ``foo``, use ``env:foo``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:95
msgid ""
"**custom**: Stored in a custom directory specified by ``--config-scope``. If "
"multiple scopes are listed on the command line, they are ordered from lowest "
"to highest precedence."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:98
msgid ""
"**command line**: Build settings specified on the command line take "
"precedence over all other scopes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:100
msgid ""
"Each configuration directory may contain several configuration files, such "
"as ``config.yaml``, ``packages.yaml``, or ``mirrors.yaml``. When "
"configurations conflict, settings from higher-precedence scopes override "
"lower-precedence settings."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:103
msgid ""
"All of these except ``spack`` and ``defaults`` are initially empty, so you "
"don't have to think about the others unless you need them. The most commonly "
"used scopes are ``environment``, ``user``, and ``spack``. If you forget, you "
"can always see the available configuration scopes in order of precedece wiht "
"the ``spack config scopes`` command::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:107
msgid ""
"> spack config scopes -p\n"
"Scope            Path\n"
"command_line\n"
"spack            /home/username/spack/etc/spack\n"
"user             /home/username/.spack/\n"
"site             /home/username/spack/etc/spack/site/\n"
"defaults         /home/username/spack/etc/spack/defaults/\n"
"defaults:darwin  /home/username/spack/etc/spack/defaults/darwin/\n"
"defaults:base    /home/username/spack/etc/spack/defaults/base/\n"
"_builtin"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:118
msgid ""
"Commands that modify scopes (e.g., ``spack compilers``, ``spack repo``, "
"``spack external find``, etc.) take a ``--scope=<name>`` parameter that you "
"can use to control which scope is modified. By default, they modify the "
"highest-precedence available scope that is not read-only (like `defaults`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:124
msgid "Custom scopes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:126
msgid ""
"You may add configuration scopes directly on the command line with the ``--"
"config-scope`` argument, or ``-C`` for short. Custom command-line scopes "
"override any active environments, as well as the ``defaults``, ``system``, "
"``site``, ``user``, and ``spack`` scopes,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:129
msgid ""
"For example, the following adds two configuration scopes, named ``scope-a`` "
"and ``scope-b``, to a ``spack spec`` command:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:131
msgid "$ spack -C ~/myscopes/scope-a -C ~/myscopes/scope-b spec ncurses"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:135
msgid ""
"Custom scopes come *after* the ``spack`` command and *before* the "
"subcommand, and they specify a single path to a directory containing "
"configuration files. You can add the same configuration files to that "
"directory that you can add to any other scope (e.g., ``config.yaml``, "
"``packages.yaml``, etc.)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:138
msgid "If multiple scopes are provided:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:140
msgid "Each must be preceded with the ``--config-scope`` or ``-C`` flag."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:141
msgid "They must be ordered from lowest to highest precedence."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:144
msgid "Example: scopes for release and development"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:146
msgid ""
"Suppose that you need to support simultaneous building of release and "
"development versions of ``mypackage``, where ``mypackage`` depends on ``pkg-"
"a``, which in turn depends on ``pkg-b``. You could create the following "
"files:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:149
msgid "``~/myscopes/release/packages.yaml``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:149
msgid ""
"packages:\n"
"  mypackage:\n"
"    prefer: [\"@1.7\"]\n"
"  pkg-a:\n"
"    prefer: [\"@2.3\"]\n"
"  pkg-b:\n"
"    prefer: [\"@0.8\"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:161
msgid "``~/myscopes/develop/packages.yaml``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:161
msgid ""
"packages:\n"
"  mypackage:\n"
"    prefer: [\"@develop\"]\n"
"  pkg-a:\n"
"    prefer: [\"@develop\"]\n"
"  pkg-b:\n"
"    prefer: [\"@develop\"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:173
msgid ""
"You can switch between ``release`` and ``develop`` configurations using "
"configuration arguments. You would type ``spack -C ~/myscopes/release`` when "
"you want to build the designated release versions of ``mypackage``, ``pkg-"
"a``, and ``pkg-b``, and you would type ``spack -C ~/myscopes/develop`` when "
"you want to build all of these packages at the ``develop`` version."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:177
msgid "Example: swapping MPI providers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:179
msgid ""
"Suppose that you need to build two software packages, ``pkg-a`` and ``pkg-"
"b``. For ``pkg-b`` you want a newer Python version and a different MPI "
"implementation than for ``pkg-a``. You can create different configuration "
"scopes for use with ``pkg-a`` and ``pkg-b``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:183
msgid "``~/myscopes/pkg-a/packages.yaml``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:183
msgid ""
"packages:\n"
"  python:\n"
"    require: [\"@3.11\"]\n"
"  mpi:\n"
"    require: [openmpi]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:193
msgid "``~/myscopes/pkg-b/packages.yaml``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:193
msgid ""
"packages:\n"
"  python:\n"
"    require: [\"@3.13\"]\n"
"  mpi:\n"
"    require: [mpich]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:207
msgid "Plugin scopes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:210
msgid "Python version >= 3.8 is required to enable plugin configuration."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:212
msgid ""
"Spack can be made aware of configuration scopes that are installed as part "
"of a Python package. To do so, register a function that returns the scope's "
"path to the ``\"spack.config\"`` entry point. Consider the Python package "
"``my_package`` that includes Spack configurations:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:216
msgid ""
"my-package/\n"
"├── src\n"
"│   ├── my_package\n"
"│   │   ├── __init__.py\n"
"│   │   └── spack/\n"
"│   │   │   └── config.yaml\n"
"└── pyproject.toml"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:226
msgid ""
"Adding the following to ``my_package``'s ``pyproject.toml`` will make "
"``my_package``'s ``spack/`` configurations visible to Spack when "
"``my_package`` is installed:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:228
msgid ""
"[project.entry_points.\"spack.config\"]\n"
"my_package = \"my_package:get_config_path\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:233
msgid ""
"The function ``my_package.get_config_path`` (matching the entry point "
"definition) in ``my_package/__init__.py`` might look like:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:235
msgid ""
"import importlib.resources\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def get_config_path():\n"
"    dirname = importlib.resources.files(\"my_package\").joinpath(\"spack\")\n"
"    if dirname.exists():\n"
"        return str(dirname)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:248
msgid "Platform-specific Configuration"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:252
msgid ""
"Prior to v1.0, each scope above -- except environment scopes -- had a "
"corresponding platform-specific scope (e.g., ``defaults/linux``, ``system/"
"windows``). This can now be accomplished through a suitably placed :ref:"
"`include.yaml <include-yaml>` file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:255
msgid ""
"There is often a need for platform-specific configuration settings. For "
"example, on most platforms, GCC is the preferred compiler. However, on macOS "
"(darwin), Clang often works for more packages, and is set as the default "
"compiler. This configuration is set in ``$(prefix)/etc/spack/defaults/darwin/"
"packages.yaml``, which is included by ``$(prefix)/etc/spack/defaults/include."
"yaml``. Since it is an included configuration of the ``defaults`` scope, "
"settings in the ``defaults`` scope will take precedence."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:261
msgid "For example, if ``$(prefix)/etc/spack/defaults/include.yaml`` contains:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:263
msgid ""
"include:\n"
"- path: \"${platform}\"\n"
"  optional: true\n"
"- path: base"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:270
msgid ""
"then, on macOS (``darwin``), configuration settings for files under the "
"``$(prefix)/etc/spack/defaults/darwin`` directory would be picked up if they "
"are present. Because ``${platform}`` is above the ``base`` include in the "
"list, ``${platform}`` settings will override anything in ``base`` if there "
"are conflicts."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:275
msgid ""
"You can get the name to use for ``<platform>`` by running ``spack arch --"
"platform``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:277
msgid ""
"Platform-specific configuration files can similarly be set up for any other "
"scope by creating an ``include.yaml`` similar to the one above for "
"``defaults`` -- under the appropriate configuration paths (see :ref:`config-"
"overrides`) and creating a subdirectory with the platform name that contains "
"the configurations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:282
msgid "Scope Precedence"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:284
msgid ""
"When Spack queries for configuration parameters, it searches in higher-"
"precedence scopes first. So, settings in a higher-precedence file can "
"override those with the same key in a lower-precedence one. For list-valued "
"settings, Spack merges lists by *prepending* items from higher-precedence "
"configurations to items from lower-precedence configurations by default. "
"Completely ignoring lower-precedence configuration options is supported with "
"the ``::`` notation for keys (see :ref:`config-overrides` below)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:291
msgid ""
"Settings in a scope take precedence over those provided in any included "
"configuration files (i.e., files listed in :ref:`include.yaml <include-"
"yaml>` or an ``include:`` section in ``spack.yaml``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:293
msgid ""
"There are also special notations for string concatenation and precedence "
"override:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:295
msgid ""
"``+:`` will force *prepending* strings or lists. For lists, this is the "
"default behavior."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:297
msgid "``-:`` works similarly, but for *appending* values."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:299
msgid "See :ref:`config-prepend-append` for more details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:302
msgid "Simple keys"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:304
msgid ""
"Let's look at an example of overriding a single key in a Spack configuration "
"file. If your configurations look like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:307 ../../../configuration.rst:422
msgid "``$(prefix)/etc/spack/defaults/config.yaml``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:319 ../../../configuration.rst:353
#: ../../../configuration.rst:377 ../../../configuration.rst:397
#: ../../../configuration.rst:434 ../../../configuration.rst:465
msgid "``~/.spack/config.yaml``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:319
msgid ""
"config:\n"
"  install_tree:\n"
"    root: /some/other/directory"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:328
msgid ""
"Spack will only override ``install_tree`` in the ``config`` section, and "
"will take the site preferences for other settings. You can see the final, "
"combined configuration with the ``spack config get <configtype>`` command:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:331
msgid ""
"$ spack config get config\n"
"config:\n"
"  install_tree:\n"
"    root: /some/other/directory\n"
"  build_stage:\n"
"  - $tempdir/$user/spack-stage\n"
"  - ~/.spack/stage"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:346
msgid "String Concatenation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:348
msgid ""
"Above, the user ``config.yaml`` *completely* overrides specific settings in "
"the default ``config.yaml``. Sometimes, it is useful to add a suffix/prefix "
"to a path or name. To do this, you can use the ``-:`` notation for *append* "
"string concatenation at the end of a key in a configuration file. For "
"example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:353
msgid ""
"config:\n"
"  install_tree:\n"
"    root-: /my/custom/suffix/"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:362
msgid ""
"Spack will then append to the lower-precedence configuration under the "
"``root`` key:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:364
msgid ""
"$ spack config get config\n"
"config:\n"
"  install_tree:\n"
"    root: /some/other/directory/my/custom/suffix\n"
"  build_stage:\n"
"  - $tempdir/$user/spack-stage\n"
"  - ~/.spack/stage"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:375
msgid "Similarly, ``+:`` can be used to *prepend* to a path or name:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:377
msgid ""
"config:\n"
"  install_tree:\n"
"    root+: /my/custom/suffix/"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:390
msgid "Overriding entire sections"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:392
msgid ""
"Above, the user ``config.yaml`` only overrides specific settings in the "
"default ``config.yaml``. Sometimes, it is useful to *completely* override "
"lower-precedence settings. To do this, you can use *two* colons at the end "
"of a key in a configuration file. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:397
msgid ""
"config::\n"
"  install_tree:\n"
"    root: /some/other/directory"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:406
msgid ""
"Spack will ignore all lower-precedence configuration under the ``config::`` "
"section:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:408
msgid ""
"$ spack config get config\n"
"config:\n"
"  install_tree:\n"
"    root: /some/other/directory"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:417
msgid "List-valued settings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:419
msgid ""
"Let's revisit the ``config.yaml`` example one more time. The ``build_stage`` "
"setting's value is an ordered list of directories:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:422
msgid ""
"config:\n"
"  build_stage:\n"
"  - $tempdir/$user/spack-stage\n"
"  - ~/.spack/stage"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:432
msgid ""
"Suppose the user configuration adds its *own* list of ``build_stage`` paths:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:434
msgid ""
"config:\n"
"  build_stage:\n"
"  - /lustre-scratch/$user/spack\n"
"  - ~/mystage"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:444
msgid ""
"Spack will first look at the paths in the defaults ``config.yaml``, then the "
"paths in the user's ``~/.spack/config.yaml``. The list in the higher-"
"precedence scope is *prepended* to the defaults. ``spack config get config`` "
"shows the result:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:448
msgid ""
"$ spack config get config\n"
"config:\n"
"  install_tree:\n"
"    root: /some/other/directory\n"
"  build_stage:\n"
"  - /lustre-scratch/$user/spack\n"
"  - ~/mystage\n"
"  - $tempdir/$user/spack-stage\n"
"  - ~/.spack/stage"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:462
msgid ""
"As in :ref:`config-overrides`, the higher-precedence scope can *completely* "
"override the lower-precedence scope using ``::``. So if the user config "
"looked like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:465
msgid ""
"config:\n"
"  build_stage::\n"
"  - /lustre-scratch/$user/spack\n"
"  - ~/mystage"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:476
msgid "The merged configuration would look like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:478
msgid ""
"$ spack config get config\n"
"config:\n"
"  install_tree:\n"
"    root: /some/other/directory\n"
"  build_stage:\n"
"    - /lustre-scratch/$user/spack\n"
"    - ~/mystage"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:493
msgid "Config File Variables"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:495
msgid ""
"Spack understands several variables which can be used in config file paths "
"wherever they appear. There are three sets of these variables: Spack-"
"specific variables, environment variables, and user path variables. Spack-"
"specific variables and environment variables are both indicated by prefixing "
"the variable name with ``$``. User path variables are indicated at the start "
"of the path with ``~`` or ``~user``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:501
msgid "Spack-specific variables"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:503
msgid "Spack understands over a dozen special variables. These are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:506
msgid ""
"``$env``: name of the currently active :ref:`environment <environments>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:507
msgid "``$spack``: path to the prefix of this Spack installation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:508
msgid ""
"``$tempdir``: default system temporary directory (as specified in Python's "
"`tempfile.tempdir <https://docs.python.org/2/library/tempfile.html#tempfile."
"tempdir>`_ variable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:509
msgid "``$user``: name of the current user"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:510
msgid ""
"``$user_cache_path``: user cache directory (``~/.spack`` unless :ref:"
"`overridden <local-config-overrides>`)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:511
msgid ""
"``$architecture``: the architecture triple of the current host, as detected "
"by Spack."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:512
msgid "``$arch``: alias for ``$architecture``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:513
msgid "``$platform``: the platform of the current host, as detected by Spack."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:514
msgid ""
"``$operating_system``: the operating system of the current host, as detected "
"by the ``distro`` Python module."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:515
msgid "``$os``: alias for ``$operating_system``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:516
msgid ""
"``$target``: the ISA target for the current host, as detected by ArchSpec. E."
"g. ``skylake`` or ``neoverse-n1``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:519
msgid ""
"``$target_family``. The target family for the current host, as detected by "
"ArchSpec. E.g. ``x86_64`` or ``aarch64``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:523
msgid "``$date``: the current date in the format YYYY-MM-DD"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:524
msgid ""
"``$spack_short_version``: the Spack version truncated to the first "
"components."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:527
msgid ""
"Note that, as with shell variables, you can write these as ``$varname`` or "
"with braces to distinguish the variable from surrounding characters: "
"``${varname}``. Their names are also case insensitive, meaning that "
"``$SPACK`` works just as well as ``$spack``. These special variables are "
"substituted first, so any environment variables with the same name will not "
"be used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:532
msgid "Environment variables"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:534
msgid ""
"After Spack-specific variables are evaluated, environment variables are "
"expanded. These are formatted like Spack-specific variables, e.g., "
"``${varname}``. You can use this to insert environment variables in your "
"Spack configuration."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:539
msgid "User home directories"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:541
msgid ""
"Spack performs Unix-style tilde expansion on paths in configuration files. "
"This means that tilde (``~``) will expand to the current user's home "
"directory, and ``~user`` will expand to a specified user's home directory. "
"The ``~`` must appear at the beginning of the path, or Spack will not expand "
"it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:548
msgid "Environment Modifications"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:550
msgid ""
"Spack allows users to prescribe custom environment modifications in a few "
"places within its configuration files. Every time these modifications are "
"allowed, they are specified as a dictionary, like in the following example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:553
msgid ""
"environment:\n"
"  set:\n"
"    LICENSE_FILE: \"/path/to/license\"\n"
"  unset:\n"
"  - CPATH\n"
"  - LIBRARY_PATH\n"
"  append_path:\n"
"    PATH: \"/new/bin/dir\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:564
msgid ""
"The possible actions that are permitted are ``set``, ``unset``, "
"``append_path``, ``prepend_path``, and finally ``remove_path``. They all "
"require a dictionary of variable names mapped to the values used for the "
"modification, with the exception of ``unset``, which requires just a list of "
"variable names. No particular order is ensured for the execution of each of "
"these modifications."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:569
msgid "Seeing Spack's Configuration"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:571
msgid ""
"With so many scopes overriding each other, it can sometimes be difficult to "
"understand what Spack's final configuration looks like."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:573
msgid ""
"Spack provides two useful ways to view the final \"merged\" version of any "
"configuration file: ``spack config get`` and ``spack config blame``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:578
msgid "``spack config get``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:580
msgid ""
"``spack config get`` shows a fully merged configuration file, taking into "
"account all scopes. For example, to see the fully merged ``config.yaml``, "
"you can type:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:583
msgid ""
"$ spack config get config\n"
"config:\n"
"  debug: false\n"
"  checksum: true\n"
"  verify_ssl: true\n"
"  dirty: false\n"
"  build_jobs: 8\n"
"  install_tree:\n"
"    root: $spack/opt/spack\n"
"  template_dirs:\n"
"  - $spack/templates\n"
"  directory_layout: {architecture}/{compiler.name}-{compiler.version}/{name}-"
"{version}-{hash}\n"
"  build_stage:\n"
"  - $tempdir/$user/spack-stage\n"
"  - ~/.spack/stage\n"
"  - $spack/var/spack/stage\n"
"  source_cache: $spack/var/spack/cache\n"
"  misc_cache: ~/.spack/cache\n"
"  locks: true"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:605
msgid "Likewise, this will show the fully merged ``packages.yaml``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:607
msgid "$ spack config get packages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:611
msgid ""
"You can use this in conjunction with the ``-C`` / ``--config-scope`` "
"argument to see how your scope will affect Spack's configuration:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:613
msgid "$ spack -C /path/to/my/scope config get packages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:621
msgid "``spack config blame``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:623
msgid ""
"``spack config blame`` functions much like ``spack config get``, but it "
"shows exactly which configuration file each setting came from. If you do not "
"know why Spack is behaving a certain way, this command can help you track "
"down the source of the configuration:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:626
msgid ""
"$ spack --insecure -C ./my-scope -C ./my-scope-2 config blame config\n"
"==> Warning: You asked for --insecure. Will NOT check SSL certificates.\n"
"---                                                   config:\n"
"_builtin                                                debug: False\n"
"/home/myuser/spack/etc/spack/defaults/config.yaml:72    checksum: True\n"
"command_line                                            verify_ssl: False\n"
"./my-scope-2/config.yaml:2                              dirty: False\n"
"_builtin                                                build_jobs: 8\n"
"./my-scope/config.yaml:2                                install_tree: /path/"
"to/some/tree\n"
"/home/myuser/spack/etc/spack/defaults/config.yaml:23    template_dirs:\n"
"/home/myuser/spack/etc/spack/defaults/config.yaml:24    - $spack/templates\n"
"/home/myuser/spack/etc/spack/defaults/config.yaml:28    directory_layout: "
"{architecture}/{compiler.name}-{compiler.version}/{name}-{version}-{hash}\n"
"/home/myuser/spack/etc/spack/defaults/config.yaml:49    build_stage:\n"
"/home/myuser/spack/etc/spack/defaults/config.yaml:50    - $tempdir/$user/"
"spack-stage\n"
"/home/myuser/spack/etc/spack/defaults/config.yaml:51    - ~/.spack/stage\n"
"/home/myuser/spack/etc/spack/defaults/config.yaml:52    - $spack/var/spack/"
"stage\n"
"/home/myuser/spack/etc/spack/defaults/config.yaml:57    source_cache: $spack/"
"var/spack/cache\n"
"/home/myuser/spack/etc/spack/defaults/config.yaml:62    misc_cache: ~/.spack/"
"cache\n"
"/home/myuser/spack/etc/spack/defaults/config.yaml:86    locks: True"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:648
msgid ""
"You can see above that the ``build_jobs`` and ``debug`` settings are built-"
"in and are not overridden by a configuration file. The ``verify_ssl`` "
"setting comes from the ``--insecure`` option on the command line. The "
"``dirty`` and ``install_tree`` settings come from the custom scopes ``./my-"
"scope`` and ``./my-scope-2``, and all other configuration options come from "
"the default configuration files that ship with Spack."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:655
msgid "Overriding Local Configuration"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:657
msgid ""
"Spack's ``system`` and ``user`` scopes provide ways for administrators and "
"users to set global defaults for all Spack instances, but for use cases "
"where one wants a clean Spack installation, these scopes can be undesirable. "
"For example, users may want to opt out of global system configuration, or "
"they may want to ignore their own home directory settings when running in a "
"continuous integration environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:660
msgid ""
"Spack also, by default, keeps various caches and user data in ``~/.spack``, "
"but users may want to override these locations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:662
msgid ""
"Spack provides three environment variables that allow you to override or opt "
"out of configuration locations:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:664
msgid ""
"``SPACK_USER_CONFIG_PATH``: Override the path to use for the ``user`` scope "
"(``~/.spack`` by default)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:665
msgid ""
"``SPACK_SYSTEM_CONFIG_PATH``: Override the path to use for the ``system`` "
"scope (``/etc/spack`` by default)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:666
msgid ""
"``SPACK_DISABLE_LOCAL_CONFIG``: Set this environment variable to completely "
"disable **both** the system and user configuration directories. Spack will "
"then only consider its own defaults and ``site`` configuration locations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:669
msgid "And one that allows you to move the default cache location:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:671
msgid ""
"``SPACK_USER_CACHE_PATH``: Override the default path to use for user data "
"(misc_cache, tests, reports, etc.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:673
msgid ""
"With these settings, if you want to isolate Spack in a CI environment, you "
"can do this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuration.rst:675
msgid ""
"$ export SPACK_DISABLE_LOCAL_CONFIG=true\n"
"$ export SPACK_USER_CACHE_PATH=/tmp/spack"
msgstr ""
